Exhaled human breath (consisting mainly of N2, O2, CO2 and H2O) was collected as a background to examine the NH3-sensing performance of the sensor in a practical application. As illustrated in Fig. 4
                        a, two Tedlar bags (namely T1 and T2, volume: 1L) were used to collect the exhaled breath of the subjects, and then NH3 was injected into T2. The response (IFITC/ICDs
                        ) versus NH3 concentration curves were recorded in Fig. 4b. Due to the complicated gaseous environment in the human breath, it was challenging for the RNS to distinguish between exhaled breath with a very low concentration of additional NH3 and normal exhaled breath (Table S). Even so, the fabricated ratiometric sensor could clearly identify an additional 5 ppm NH3 in the exhaled breath.
